Commands are executable programs that perform specific tasks. 
These executable programs can be called using their name as per the provided syntax. 

General Syntax: 
# <commands>   -<options>  -<argument>  <multiple arguments> 

Commands- To run the command. 
Options - To adjust the behaviour of the commands. 
Arguments - The behaviour, file folder name. (path)

BASIC COMMANDS :
Sudo su - / sudo -i
Mkdir dir_name
Mkdir dir1 dir2 dir3
Mkdir -p parent/child
ls dir
Cd 
Cd..
Rmdir
Rm -rf

#tty                        	This command displays the current user terminal number. 
#who    	                    Display current logged in all users with their details. 
#who am i                    	Display current user details. 
#whoami 	                     Display current user username. 
#w	                          Display all current user details with their time schedule. 
#wh<tab> <tab>                	To see similar commands or autocomplete cmd. 
#clear or ctrl+l               It clears screen but not background data. 
#cal 	                         It displays current month of calendar. 
#cal <year> 	                 It displays specified year calendar. 
#cal <month> <year>            It displays specific months calendar in particular year 
#cal  -3 	                     It displays previous, current and next month's calendar of current year. 
#cal -j <year> 	              It displays Julian days of particular year. 
#date                       	It shows current date and time. 
#date -s  "DDMMYYYY  HH:MM:SS" 	It set date and time. 
#reboot OR #init 6 	          To restart the system 
#power off OR #init 0        	To power off system. 
#shutdown                    	It shutdown system after 1 min 
#shutdown -h 10 	            It shutdown system after 10 min and broadcast 
#shutdown -c                 	message to all users. 
#shutdown now OR shutdown -h 	It cancels shutdown timer and broadcast message to all users. 
#logout OR exit OR ctrl + d 	It immediately shutdown system. 
#hostname OR hostname -s    	Logout from currently logged in user. Shows machine name 
	

